Quote: CANTHERINES CONVEXIROSTRIS (Gunther[u-dieresis]). <i>Leather-jacket; Kokiri</i>[o-macron]. Large numbers are skinned and sold in Auckland as `cream-fish.' ... Distribution: New Zealand coasts (less common, South Island).
Notes: Phillipps Notes on the Edible Fishes

Date: 0/0/1947
Source: Native Animals of NZ
Author: POWELL
Vol / Page: 72
Edition:
Quote: LEATHER-JACKET (<i>Cantherines convexirostris</i>), Kokiri of the Maoris, is a curious rough-skinned fish with a small mouth and a trigger-like spine on the back which can be locked into a vertical position at will. This fish resembles brown suede leather except for the fins, which are bright yellow. It is a good food fish and is sold in the Auckland markets in the form of skinned fillets under the name of `cream-fish.'
Notes:

